04789nam a22007215i 9780271035031DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710350317 a10.1515/97802710350312doi  a(DE-B1597)584009  a(OCoLC)1269268845  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1190b.C43 2008eb 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a306.4/6132221 aChambers, Clare, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSex, Culture, and Justice :bThe Limits of Choice /cClare Chambers. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Theories of Social Construction -- t1. Creativity, Cultural Practice, and the Body: Foucault and Three Problems with the Liberal Focus on Choice -- t2. Masculine Domination, Radical Feminism, and Change -- t3. Social Construction, Normativity, and Difference -- tPart Two. Liberalism, Culture, and Autonomy -- t4. All Must Have Prizes: The Liberal Case for Interference in Cultural Practices -- t5. Two Orders of Autonomy and Political Liberalism: Breast Implants Versus Female Genital Mutilation -- t6. Paternalism and Autonomy -- t7. Liberal Perfectionism and the Autonomy of Restricted Lives -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAutonomy is fundamental to liberalism. But autonomous individuals often choose to do things that harm themselves or undermine their equality. In particular, women often choose to participate in practices of sexual inequality-cosmetic surgery, gendered patterns of work and childcare, makeup, restrictive clothing, or the sexual subordination required by membership in certain religious groups. In this book, Clare Chambers argues that this predicament poses a fundamental challenge to many existing liberal and multicultural theories that dominate contemporary political philosophy.Chambers argues that a theory of justice cannot ignore the influence of culture and the role it plays in shaping choices. If cultures shape choices, it is problematic to use those choices as the measure of the justice of the culture. Drawing upon feminist critiques of gender inequality and poststructuralist theories of social construction, she argues that we should accept some of the multicultural claims about the importance of culture in shaping our actions and identities, but that we should reach the opposite normative conclusion to that of multiculturalists and many liberals. Rather than using the idea of social construction to justify cultural respect or protection, we should use it to ground a critical stance toward cultural norms. The book presents radical proposals for state action to promote sexual and cultural justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAutonomy (Philosophy). 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)xSocial aspects. 0aFeminist theory. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspects. 0aLiberalismxPhilosophy. 0aSex rolexPhilosophy. 0aSocial norms. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271035031zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271035031423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271035031/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEB